Here's the complete migration with key pitfalls called out:

## ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Migration

```csharp
// ReportController.cs
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // PITFALL 1: No more event-based handlers (WebForms model is gone).
    // Use action methods returning IActionResult instead.

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // PITFALL 2: Response.Clear(), Response.End(), Response.Write() don't exist.
        // Response.End() used to throw ThreadAbortException internally — that
        // entire pattern is gone. Return a FileResult instead.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // PITFALL 3: Response.Redirect(url, endResponse: true) called
            // Thread.Abort to stop execution. In .NET Core:
            //   - Thread.Abort is gone entirely (throws PlatformNotSupportedException)
            //   - RedirectResult doesn't terminate execution — it just sets the
            //     302 response. Code AFTER a return continues if you forget "return".
            return RedirectPermanent("/login"); // or Redirect() for 302
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // PITFALL 4: Never catch ThreadAbortException in .NET Core.
        // It doesn't exist. If your code catches it, it's dead code at best
        // or masks real bugs at worst. Remove the catch block entirely.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls Summary

| .NET Framework Pattern | .NET 8 Equivalent | Trap |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | Return `IActionResult` | `Response.End()` doesn't exist; `HttpResponse.CompleteAsync()` exists but is rarely needed |
| `Response.Write(data)` | `return Content(data)` or `File(...)` | Writing directly to `Response.Body` is possible but bypasses content negotiation |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `return Redirect(url)` | No execution halt — code after `Redirect()` **keeps running** unless you `return` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | **Delete it** | `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET Core |
| `Response.AddHeader(...)` | `Response.Headers.Append(...)` | Only if manually writing responses; `File()` handles headers automatically |
| `Response.Clear()` | N/A | Response buffering model is different; not needed with `IActionResult` |

## Critical Behavioral Change

```
// .NET Framework — this code after Redirect never runs (Thread.Abort kills it):
Response.Redirect("/login", true);
DoSomethingDangerous(); // never reached

// .NET Core — this WILL run if you forget "return":
Redirect("/login");
DoSomethingDangerous(); // STILL EXECUTES — silent bug
```

**Always `return` your `IActionResult`.** The redirect just sets a 302 header; it does not stop method execution.

## Startup Registration

```csharp
// Program.cs
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
builder.Services.AddControllersWithViews();
// If you had FormsAuthentication, migrate to:
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(CookieAuthenticationDefaults.AuthenticationScheme)
    .AddCookie(options => options.LoginPath = "/login");

var app = builder.Build();
app.UseAuthentication();
app.UseAuthorization();
app.MapControllers();
app.Run();
```

The biggest silent bug source: **forgetting `return` before redirect/result calls**, since .NET Core never aborts threads to stop execution flow.
